Note:
CMake Parser - Parse CMake build scripts into AST

This file provides complete CMake parsing with full AST construction.

Features:
- Complete CMake command parsing with arguments
- Control flow (if/elseif/else/endif, foreach, while)
- Function and macro definitions
- Variable references and generator expressions
- Nested command calls
- Argument lists (quoted, unquoted, bracket)

AST Node Types:
- Program: Root node containing all statements
- Command: CMake command with name and arguments
- If: Conditional with condition, then block, else block
- Foreach: Loop with iterator, iterable, body
- While: Loop with condition and body
- Function: Function definition with parameters and body
- Macro: Macro definition with parameters and body
- Argument: Command argument (string, variable, expression)
- Block: List of statements

Dependencies:
- compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/cmake/cmake_lexer.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/cmake/cmake_lexer.runa" as Lexer
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST Node Type Constants
Note: ============================================================================

Constant NODE_PROGRAM as Integer is 1000
Constant NODE_COMMAND as Integer is 1001
Constant NODE_IF as Integer is 1002
Constant NODE_FOREACH as Integer is 1003
Constant NODE_WHILE as Integer is 1004
Constant NODE_FUNCTION as Integer is 1005
Constant NODE_MACRO as Integer is 1006
Constant NODE_ARGUMENT as Integer is 1007
Constant NODE_BLOCK as Integer is 1008
Constant NODE_VARIABLE as Integer is 1009
Constant NODE_GENERATOR_EXPR as Integer is 1010

Note: Argument types
Constant ARG_STRING as Integer is 2000
Constant ARG_VARIABLE as Integer is 2001
Constant ARG_GENERATOR_EXPR as Integer is 2002
Constant ARG_IDENTIFIER as Integer is 2003

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parser State
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Minimal parser state: a borrowed lexer plus the cached current_token
and a sticky had_error flag. CMake's grammar is shallow (no nested
expression precedence) so the parser needs no expression stack.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
3 x i64 record (24 bytes). offsets: 0 = lexer (borrowed), 8 =
current_token (borrowed from lexer's stream), 16 = had_error bool.
@End Implementation

Type called "CMakeParser":
    lexer as Integer
    current_token as Integer
    had_error as Integer
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST Node Structures
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The program (root) node is a flat sequence of top-level statements.
CMake has no module/namespace concept, so the root just holds a List
of children.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
3 x i64 record (24 bytes). offsets: 0 = NODE_PROGRAM discriminator,
8 = statements List handle (lazily created on first add), 16 =
statement_count maintained alongside the list for O(1) size queries.
@End Implementation

Type called "CMakeProgram":
    node_type as Integer     Note: NODE_PROGRAM
    statements as Integer    Note: List of statement nodes
    statement_count as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Most CMake statements are commands of the form `name(arg1 arg2 ...)`.
The command record carries the name string plus the argument list,
together with source position for diagnostics.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
5 x i64 record (40 bytes). offsets: 0 = NODE_COMMAND, 8 = command_name
string handle, 16 = arguments List (lazy), 24 = argument_count,
32 = line. Column is implicitly the byte offset of the command start.
@End Implementation

Type called "CMakeCommand":
    node_type as Integer     Note: NODE_COMMAND
    command_name as Integer  Note: String pointer
    arguments as Integer     Note: List of argument nodes
    argument_count as Integer
    line as Integer
    column as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
CMake if/elseif/else uses parenthesised condition lists rather than
boolean expressions. elseif chains are modelled as nested CMakeIf
nodes in the else slot so traversal code only needs to know two
branches per if-node.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
5 x i64 record (40 bytes). offsets: 0 = NODE_IF, 8 = condition List,
16 = then_block CMakeBlock handle, 24 = elseif_clauses (unused after
the elseif-as-nested-if refactor), 32 = else_block handle (0 if no
else). parse_if walks the elseif chain by attaching nested CMakeIf
records via set_if_else.
@End Implementation

Type called "CMakeIf":
    node_type as Integer     Note: NODE_IF
    condition as Integer     Note: List of condition arguments
    then_block as Integer    Note: Block node
    elseif_clauses as Integer Note: List of (condition, block) pairs
    else_block as Integer    Note: Block node (0 if no else)
End Type

@Reasoning:
foreach(var item1 item2 ...) ... endforeach(): iterator_var holds the
loop variable name, iterable is the list of items, body is the loop
body block.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
4 x i64 record (32 bytes). offsets: 0 = NODE_FOREACH,
8 = iterator_var name string, 16 = iterable List of CMakeArguments,
24 = body CMakeBlock.
@End Implementation

Type called "CMakeForeach":
    node_type as Integer     Note: NODE_FOREACH
    iterator_var as Integer  Note: String pointer
    iterable as Integer      Note: List of arguments
    body as Integer          Note: Block node
End Type

@Reasoning:
while(condition) ... endwhile() shape, mirroring CMakeIf's condition
representation as an argument list rather than a typed boolean.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
3 x i64 record (24 bytes). offsets: 0 = NODE_WHILE,
8 = condition List, 16 = body CMakeBlock.
@End Implementation

Type called "CMakeWhile":
    node_type as Integer     Note: NODE_WHILE
    condition as Integer     Note: List of condition arguments
    body as Integer          Note: Block node
End Type

@Reasoning:
function(name args...) ... endfunction(). CMake functions have their
own scope and explicit-argument access — distinguished from macros
(CMakeMacro) which are scoped textually.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
4 x i64 record (32 bytes). offsets: 0 = NODE_FUNCTION,
8 = function_name string, 16 = parameters List of CMakeArguments,
24 = body CMakeBlock.
@End Implementation

Type called "CMakeFunction":
    node_type as Integer     Note: NODE_FUNCTION
    function_name as Integer Note: String pointer
    parameters as Integer    Note: List of parameter names
    body as Integer          Note: Block node
End Type

@Reasoning:
macro(name args...) ... endmacro(). Identical structure to CMakeFunction
but with different semantics — macros are unscoped and inherit caller
variables directly. Kept as a separate type so callers can switch on
the structural difference.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
4 x i64 record (32 bytes). offsets: 0 = NODE_MACRO,
8 = macro_name string, 16 = parameters List, 24 = body CMakeBlock.
@End Implementation

Type called "CMakeMacro":
    node_type as Integer     Note: NODE_MACRO
    macro_name as Integer    Note: String pointer
    parameters as Integer    Note: List of parameter names
    body as Integer          Note: Block node
End Type

@Reasoning:
Every command/control-flow argument carries a kind tag distinguishing
strings, ${VAR} variable references, $<...> generator expressions, and
bare identifiers. The kind drives how downstream code resolves the
argument at evaluation time.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
5 x i64 record (40 bytes). offsets: 0 = NODE_ARGUMENT,
8 = arg_type discriminator (ARG_STRING / ARG_VARIABLE /
ARG_GENERATOR_EXPR / ARG_IDENTIFIER), 16 = value string handle,
24 = line, 32 = column.
@End Implementation

Type called "CMakeArgument":
    node_type as Integer     Note: NODE_ARGUMENT
    arg_type as Integer      Note: ARG_STRING, ARG_VARIABLE, etc.
    value as Integer         Note: String pointer
    line as Integer
    column as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
A block is a sequence of statements used as the body of if/foreach/
while/function/macro nodes. Structurally identical to CMakeProgram
but kept as a distinct type so traversal code can distinguish the
root from nested bodies.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
3 x i64 record (24 bytes). offsets: 0 = NODE_BLOCK,
8 = statements List (lazy), 16 = statement_count.
@End Implementation

Type called "CMakeBlock":
    node_type as Integer     Note: NODE_BLOCK
    statements as Integer    Note: List of statement nodes
    statement_count as Integer
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parser Creation and Token Management
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Constructs the parser record and primes it by consuming the first
token, so parse_statement can dispatch on current_token without a
special-case initial advance.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 24 bytes via Layout. Sets lexer at offset 0, zero-initialises
current_token and had_error, then calls advance to pull the first
token into the parser. Returns 0 on allocation failure.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_parser" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create CMake parser

    Let parser_size be 24
    Let parser be proc allocate from Layout with parser_size

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 0, lexer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, 0

    Note: Advance to first token
    proc advance with parser

    Return parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
Single consumption point used by every parser helper: reads the next
token from the lexer and caches it in the parser's current_token slot.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Loads lexer from offset 0, calls Lexer.next_token, writes the result
to offset 8, returns it so the caller can capture without re-reading.
@End Implementation

Process called "advance" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Advance to next token

    Let lexer be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 0
    Let token be proc next_token from Lexer with lexer

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, token

    Return token
End Process

@Reasoning:
Read accessor for the cached current token, used pervasively by parse
helpers when they need the raw token (for value/line/column) rather
than just the type.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns the i64 at offset 8 of the parser record without modifying
any state.
@End Implementation

Process called "current_token" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get current token

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Return token
End Process

@Reasoning:
Hides the offset-0 layout of the lexer's token records from parser
code. Null token is mapped to TOKEN_EOF so callers reach EOF safely
even if the lexer hands back nothing.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null guard returns Lexer.TOKEN_EOF; on a live token reads i64 at
offset 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "token_type" takes token as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get token type from token

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return TOKEN_EOF from Lexer
    End If

    Let type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0
    Return type
End Process

@Reasoning:
Accessor for the lexeme string handle on a token. Null-safe so the
parser can chain it on optional/fallback tokens.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null guard returns 0 (null string); on a live token reads i64 at
offset 8 (lexeme handle slot).
@End Implementation

Process called "token_value" takes token as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get token value (string) from token

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Return value
End Process

@Reasoning:
Mandatory-token gate: when the grammar requires a specific token,
this helper sets had_error on mismatch (so the caller can choose to
bail) and consumes on match.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Compares token_type(current_token) with expected_type. On mismatch
writes 1 to had_error (offset 16) and returns 0. On match calls
advance (consuming the token) and returns 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "expect" takes parser as Integer, expected_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Verify current token type and advance

    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    Let type be proc token_type with token

    If type is not equal to expected_type:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, 1
        Return 0
    End If

    proc advance with parser
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Predicate for "is the current token X" used to gate optional grammar
rules. Unlike expect, never raises an error and never consumes the
token — purely a lookup.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads current_token, calls token_type, returns 1 if equal to
expected_type, 0 otherwise.
@End Implementation

Process called "match" takes parser as Integer, expected_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if current token matches type without advancing

    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    Let type be proc token_type with token

    If type is equal to expected_type:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST Node Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Empty program-root constructor used at the start of parse. Statements
list is left at 0 and created lazily on the first append to keep
single-line CMake files from allocating an empty list.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 24 bytes. Writes NODE_PROGRAM at offset 0, leaves
statements (8) and statement_count (16) at 0. Returns 0 on
allocation failure.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_program" returns Integer:
    Note: Create program (root) node

    Let program_size be 24
    Let program be proc allocate from Layout with program_size

    If program is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with program, 0, NODE_PROGRAM
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with program, 8, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with program, 16, 0

    Return program
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lazy List creation on first add; subsequent adds append directly.
Keeps the statement_count in sync with the list so traversal code can
get the count without walking.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null guards on program and statement. Reads statements list at
offset 8; if 0, calls List.create and writes it back. Appends the
statement via List.append, then bumps statement_count at offset 16
by 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "add_statement_to_program" takes program as Integer, statement as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Add statement to program

    If program is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If statement is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let statements be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with program, 8

    If statements is equal to 0:
        Set statements to proc create from List
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with program, 8, statements
    End If

    proc append from List with statements, statement

    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with program, 16
    Set count to count plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with program, 16, count

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Allocates a CMakeCommand record with the supplied name and source
position; arguments list is left at 0 for lazy creation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 40 bytes; returns 0 on failure. Writes NODE_COMMAND (0),
name string handle (8), arguments=0 (16), argument_count=0 (24),
line (32). column is intentionally not stored in this record (kept
on a per-token basis).
@End Implementation

Process called "create_command" takes name as Integer, line as Integer, column as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create command node

    Let cmd_size be 40
    Let cmd be proc allocate from Layout with cmd_size

    If cmd is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cmd, 0, NODE_COMMAND
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cmd, 8, name
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cmd, 16, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cmd, 24, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cmd, 32, line

    Return cmd
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lazy-allocate the arguments list, append the argument, and keep
argument_count in sync so the codegen pass can size buffers without
walking.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null guards. Reads arguments at offset 16; if 0, creates a new List
and writes it back. Appends via List.append, increments
argument_count at offset 24 by 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "add_argument_to_command" takes command as Integer, argument as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Add argument to command

    If command is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If argument is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let arguments be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with command, 16

    If arguments is equal to 0:
        Set arguments to proc create from List
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with command, 16, arguments
    End If

    proc append from List with arguments, argument

    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with command, 24
    Set count to count plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with command, 24, count

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Builds a CMakeArgument record carrying the discriminator (ARG_STRING /
ARG_VARIABLE / etc), value string, and source position for
diagnostics.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 40 bytes; returns 0 on failure. Writes NODE_ARGUMENT (0),
arg_type (8), value handle (16), line (24), column (32).
@End Implementation

Process called "create_argument" takes arg_type as Integer, value as Integer, line as Integer, column as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create argument node

    Let arg_size be 40
    Let arg be proc allocate from Layout with arg_size

    If arg is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with arg, 0, NODE_ARGUMENT
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with arg, 8, arg_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with arg, 16, value
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with arg, 24, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with arg, 32, column

    Return arg
End Process

@Reasoning:
Empty-block constructor used as the body of if/foreach/while/
function/macro. Same lazy-list strategy as create_program — keeps
empty bodies allocation-light.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 24 bytes. Writes NODE_BLOCK (0), statements=0 (8),
statement_count=0 (16). Returns 0 on allocation failure.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_block" returns Integer:
    Note: Create block node

    Let block_size be 24
    Let block be proc allocate from Layout with block_size

    If block is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with block, 0, NODE_BLOCK
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with block, 8, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with block, 16, 0

    Return block
End Process

@Reasoning:
Mirror of add_statement_to_program for the body block case; kept
separate so block layout can diverge from program layout if needed.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null guards on block and statement. Reads statements list at offset
8; if 0, allocates and stores it. Appends and bumps statement_count
at offset 16.
@End Implementation

Process called "add_statement_to_block" takes block as Integer, statement as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Add statement to block

    If block is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If statement is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let statements be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 8

    If statements is equal to 0:
        Set statements to proc create from List
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with block, 8, statements
    End If

    proc append from List with statements, statement

    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 16
    Set count to count plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with block, 16, count

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Builds a CMakeIf record with condition and then-block; the optional
else_block is attached later via set_if_else as the parser walks
elseif/else chains.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 40 bytes; returns 0 on failure. Writes NODE_IF (0),
condition (8), then_block (16), elseif_clauses=0 (24), else_block=0
(32). elseif_clauses remains 0 because the elseif chain is encoded
as nested CMakeIf nodes in else_block.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_if" takes condition as Integer, then_block as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create if node

    Let if_size be 40
    Let if_node be proc allocate from Layout with if_size

    If if_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with if_node, 0, NODE_IF
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with if_node, 8, condition
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with if_node, 16, then_block
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with if_node, 24, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with if_node, 32, 0

    Return if_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Mutator used by parse_if to attach the else branch (or, for elseif
chains, the nested CMakeIf that represents the next condition) after
the head if-node has been constructed.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null guard returns 0. Writes else_block at offset 32 of if_node and
returns 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "set_if_else" takes if_node as Integer, else_block as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Set else block for if node

    If if_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with if_node, 32, else_block
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Constructs a CMakeForeach with the loop variable name, the iterable
arguments list, and the body block.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 32 bytes. Writes NODE_FOREACH (0), iterator_var (8),
iterable (16), body (24). Returns 0 on allocation failure.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_foreach" takes iterator_var as Integer, iterable as Integer, body as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create foreach node

    Let foreach_size be 32
    Let foreach_node be proc allocate from Layout with foreach_size

    If foreach_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with foreach_node, 0, NODE_FOREACH
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with foreach_node, 8, iterator_var
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with foreach_node, 16, iterable
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with foreach_node, 24, body

    Return foreach_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Constructs a CMakeWhile with the condition list and body block.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 24 bytes. Writes NODE_WHILE (0), condition (8), body (16).
Returns 0 on allocation failure.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_while" takes condition as Integer, body as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create while node

    Let while_size be 24
    Let while_node be proc allocate from Layout with while_size

    If while_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with while_node, 0, NODE_WHILE
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with while_node, 8, condition
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with while_node, 16, body

    Return while_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Constructs a CMakeFunction with name, parameters list, and body
block. Distinct from create_macro to preserve the function-vs-macro
scoping difference downstream.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 32 bytes. Writes NODE_FUNCTION (0), function_name (8),
parameters (16), body (24).
@End Implementation

Process called "create_function" takes function_name as Integer, parameters as Integer, body as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create function node

    Let func_size be 32
    Let func_node be proc allocate from Layout with func_size

    If func_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with func_node, 0, NODE_FUNCTION
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with func_node, 8, function_name
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with func_node, 16, parameters
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with func_node, 24, body

    Return func_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Same shape as create_function but tagged NODE_MACRO so the codegen
treats it as a textual macro (unscoped, inherits caller variables).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 32 bytes. Writes NODE_MACRO (0), macro_name (8),
parameters (16), body (24).
@End Implementation

Process called "create_macro" takes macro_name as Integer, parameters as Integer, body as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create macro node

    Let macro_size be 32
    Let macro_node be proc allocate from Layout with macro_size

    If macro_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with macro_node, 0, NODE_MACRO
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with macro_node, 8, macro_name
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with macro_node, 16, parameters
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with macro_node, 24, body

    Return macro_node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parsing Functions
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level parse driver: walks tokens until EOF, invoking parse_statement
for each statement and tolerating unrecognised tokens by skipping
them (unless they trigger had_error, in which case the whole parse
aborts).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates a CMakeProgram root via create_program; returns 0 on
allocation failure. Loops while current token is not TOKEN_EOF: calls
parse_statement; on 0-result checks had_error and bails on hard
error, otherwise advances past the unrecognised token. On non-zero
result adds the statement to the program. Returns the populated
program record.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse entire CMake file into AST

    Let program be proc create_program

    If program is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Parse statements until EOF
    While proc match with parser, TOKEN_EOF from Lexer is equal to 0:
        Let statement be proc parse_statement with parser

        If statement is equal to 0:
            Note: Check if error occurred
            Let had_error be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16
            If had_error is equal to 1:
                Return 0
            End If
            Note: Otherwise just skip
            proc advance with parser
        Otherwise:
            proc add_statement_to_program with program, statement
        End If
    End While

    Return program
End Process

@Reasoning:
Dispatches between control-flow constructs (if/foreach/while/function/
macro) and regular commands. The token-type ranges allow built-in
CMake command keywords (SET..TARGET_COMPILE_OPTIONS) to dispatch to
parse_command without needing a separate kind tag.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads current_token's type. Sequential If checks for TOKEN_IF,
TOKEN_FOREACH, TOKEN_WHILE, TOKEN_FUNCTION, TOKEN_MACRO each routing
to the matching parse_* helper. Otherwise routes any TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
or any token in the TOKEN_SET..TOKEN_TARGET_COMPILE_OPTIONS range to
parse_command. Returns 0 for unrecognised tokens — the caller in
parse() handles the skip.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse single statement (command or control flow)

    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    Let type be proc token_type with token

    Note: Check for control flow keywords
    If type is equal to TOKEN_IF from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_if with parser
    End If

    If type is equal to TOKEN_FOREACH from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_foreach with parser
    End If

    If type is equal to TOKEN_WHILE from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_while with parser
    End If

    If type is equal to TOKEN_FUNCTION from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_function with parser
    End If

    If type is equal to TOKEN_MACRO from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_macro with parser
    End If

    Note: Otherwise parse as command
    If type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_command with parser
    End If

    Note: Also handle special command keywords
    If type is greater than or equal to TOKEN_SET from Lexer:
        If type is less than or equal to TOKEN_TARGET_COMPILE_OPTIONS from Lexer:
            Return proc parse_command with parser
        End If
    End If

    Note: Skip unrecognized tokens
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses a CMake command of the form `name(arg arg ...)`. Tolerant of
unrecognised tokens inside the argument list — it skips them rather
than aborting, to maximise the amount of structure recovered from a
malformed file.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Captures the command name lexeme and position from the current token,
advances past it, calls expect for left-paren (returns 0 on failure).
Builds a CMakeCommand. Loop until right-paren: parse_argument; if 0,
checks for TOKEN_EOF (bails) and otherwise skips a token. Non-zero
arguments are attached. Advances past the closing right-paren and
returns the command node.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_command" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse command: name(arg1 arg2 ...)

    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    Let type be proc token_type with token
    Let value be proc token_value with token
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 24

    Note: Get command name
    Let command_name be value
    proc advance with parser

    Note: Expect left parenthesis
    If proc expect with parser, TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN from Lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create command node
    Let command be proc create_command with command_name, line, column

    If command is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Parse arguments until right parenthesis
    While proc match with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN from Lexer is equal to 0:
        Let arg be proc parse_argument with parser

        If arg is equal to 0:
            Note: Check if error or EOF
            Let token2 be proc current_token with parser
            Let type2 be proc token_type with token2
            If type2 is equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
                Return 0
            End If
            Note: Skip unrecognized token
            proc advance with parser
        Otherwise:
            proc add_argument_to_command with command, arg
        End If
    End While

    Note: Consume right parenthesis
    proc advance with parser

    Return command
End Process

@Reasoning:
Each CMake command argument is one of: quoted string, ${VAR} variable
reference, $<...> generator expression, bare identifier, control-flow
keyword (e.g. NOT, AND, EQUAL as argument), or numeric literal. The
parser tags the produced CMakeArgument with the right ARG_* kind so
downstream evaluation can dispatch.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads token type/value/line/column. Sequential dispatch by token type
mapping to ARG_STRING (TOKEN_STRING/TOKEN_NUMBER), ARG_VARIABLE
(TOKEN_VARIABLE), ARG_GENERATOR_EXPR (TOKEN_GENERATOR_EXPR), or
ARG_IDENTIFIER (TOKEN_IDENTIFIER and keyword tokens in
TOKEN_IF..TOKEN_EXISTS). Each branch advances and constructs a
CMakeArgument. Returns 0 if the token doesn't match any argument
kind.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_argument" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse command argument

    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    Let type be proc token_type with token
    Let value be proc token_value with token
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 24

    Note: String literal
    If type is equal to TOKEN_STRING from Lexer:
        proc advance with parser
        Return proc create_argument with ARG_STRING, value, line, column
    End If

    Note: Variable reference
    If type is equal to TOKEN_VARIABLE from Lexer:
        proc advance with parser
        Return proc create_argument with ARG_VARIABLE, value, line, column
    End If

    Note: Generator expression
    If type is equal to TOKEN_GENERATOR_EXPR from Lexer:
        proc advance with parser
        Return proc create_argument with ARG_GENERATOR_EXPR, value, line, column
    End If

    Note: Identifier (unquoted argument)
    If type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
        proc advance with parser
        Return proc create_argument with ARG_IDENTIFIER, value, line, column
    End If

    Note: Keywords can also be arguments
    If type is greater than or equal to TOKEN_IF from Lexer:
        If type is less than or equal to TOKEN_EXISTS from Lexer:
            proc advance with parser
            Return proc create_argument with ARG_IDENTIFIER, value, line, column
        End If
    End If

    Note: Numbers
    If type is equal to TOKEN_NUMBER from Lexer:
        proc advance with parser
        Return proc create_argument with ARG_STRING, value, line, column
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Handles if(cond) ... [elseif(cond) ...]* [else() ...] endif() by
constructing nested CMakeIf nodes for each elseif. This keeps each
if-node binary (then + else) while still representing arbitrary-
length chains correctly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes the leading `if` keyword. Parses the condition as an argument
list via parse_condition_list, then the then-block via
parse_block_until_keyword. Builds a CMakeIf. Walks the elseif chain:
for each TOKEN_ELSEIF, parses its condition and body, builds a nested
CMakeIf, attaches it as the else-block of the current-tail and
rebinds the tail. On TOKEN_ELSE, optionally consumes `()` and parses
the else block, attaches it to the tail. Finally consumes endif (and
its optional `()`). Returns the head if-node.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_if" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse if statement: if(condition) ... endif()

    Note: Consume 'if' keyword
    proc advance with parser

    Note: Parse condition as argument list
    Let condition be proc parse_condition_list with parser

    If condition is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Parse then block
    Let then_block be proc parse_block_until_keyword with parser

    If then_block is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create if node
    Let if_node be proc create_if with condition, then_block

    If if_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Handle elseif/else chain by building nested if-else structure
    Let current_if be if_node
    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    Let type be proc token_type with token

    While type is equal to TOKEN_ELSEIF from Lexer:
        Note: Parse elseif as nested if in else branch
        proc advance with parser
        Let elseif_condition be proc parse_condition_list with parser
        Let elseif_then be proc parse_block_until_keyword with parser

        Note: Create nested if node for elseif
        Let nested_if be proc create_if with elseif_condition, elseif_then

        If nested_if is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        Note: Set this nested if as the else block of the previous if
        proc set_if_else with current_if, nested_if

        Note: Continue chaining with this nested if
        Set current_if to nested_if

        Set token to proc current_token with parser
        Set type to proc token_type with token
    End While

    If type is equal to TOKEN_ELSE from Lexer:
        proc advance with parser
        Note: Expect left paren (empty argument list)
        If proc match with parser, TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN from Lexer is equal to 1:
            proc advance with parser
            proc expect with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN from Lexer
        End If

        Let else_block be proc parse_block_until_keyword with parser

        Note: Set else block on the last if in the chain
        proc set_if_else with current_if, else_block
    End If

    Note: Expect endif
    Let token2 be proc current_token with parser
    Let type2 be proc token_type with token2

    If type2 is equal to TOKEN_ENDIF from Lexer:
        proc advance with parser
        Note: Consume endif's parentheses if present
        If proc match with parser, TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN from Lexer is equal to 1:
            proc advance with parser
            Note: Parse any arguments in endif (usually empty)
            While proc match with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN from Lexer is equal to 0:
                proc advance with parser
            End While
            proc advance with parser
        End If
    End If

    Return if_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses foreach(var item ...) ... endforeach(). The first argument
inside the parens is the loop variable; subsequent arguments form the
iterable list.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes `foreach`, expects/consumes `(`. Captures the loop variable
name if the first argument is an identifier. Loops collecting remaining
arguments via parse_argument into a List (iterable), skipping
unrecognised tokens. Consumes the closing `)`. Parses the body block
via parse_block_until_keyword. Consumes the `endforeach` keyword and
its optional `()`. Builds and returns a CMakeForeach.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_foreach" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse foreach statement: foreach(var items...) ... endforeach()

    Note: Consume 'foreach' keyword
    proc advance with parser

    Note: Expect left parenthesis
    If proc expect with parser, TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN from Lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Parse iterator variable (first argument)
    Let iterator_var be 0
    If proc match with parser, TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer is equal to 1:
        Let token be proc current_token with parser
        Set iterator_var to proc token_value with token
        proc advance with parser
    End If

    Note: Parse iterable (remaining arguments)
    Let iterable be proc create from List

    While proc match with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN from Lexer is equal to 0:
        Let arg be proc parse_argument with parser

        If arg is not equal to 0:
            proc append from List with iterable, arg
        Otherwise:
            proc advance with parser
        End If
    End While

    Note: Consume right parenthesis
    proc advance with parser

    Note: Parse body
    Let body be proc parse_block_until_keyword with parser

    Note: Expect endforeach
    Let token2 be proc current_token with parser
    Let type2 be proc token_type with token2

    If type2 is equal to TOKEN_ENDFOREACH from Lexer:
        proc advance with parser
        If proc match with parser, TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN from Lexer is equal to 1:
            proc advance with parser
            While proc match with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN from Lexer is equal to 0:
                proc advance with parser
            End While
            proc advance with parser
        End If
    End If

    Return proc create_foreach with iterator_var, iterable, body
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses while(condition) ... endwhile() following the same shape as
parse_if but without elseif/else branches.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes `while`, parses the condition as an argument list, parses
the body via parse_block_until_keyword. Consumes `endwhile` and its
optional `()`. Builds and returns a CMakeWhile.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_while" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse while statement: while(condition) ... endwhile()

    Note: Consume 'while' keyword
    proc advance with parser

    Note: Parse condition
    Let condition be proc parse_condition_list with parser

    If condition is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Parse body
    Let body be proc parse_block_until_keyword with parser

    Note: Expect endwhile
    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    Let type be proc token_type with token

    If type is equal to TOKEN_ENDWHILE from Lexer:
        proc advance with parser
        If proc match with parser, TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN from Lexer is equal to 1:
            proc advance with parser
            While proc match with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN from Lexer is equal to 0:
                proc advance with parser
            End While
            proc advance with parser
        End If
    End If

    Return proc create_while with condition, body
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses function definitions, mirroring parse_foreach's argument-
collection pattern: first identifier is the name, rest are parameters,
then a body block followed by `endfunction`.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes `function`, expects `(`. Captures the function name token,
collects parameter arguments via parse_argument into a List until the
matching `)`. Parses the body via parse_block_until_keyword. Consumes
`endfunction` and its optional `()`. Builds and returns a
CMakeFunction.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_function" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse function definition: function(name args...) ... endfunction()

    Note: Consume 'function' keyword
    proc advance with parser

    Note: Expect left parenthesis
    If proc expect with parser, TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN from Lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Parse function name (first argument)
    Let function_name be 0
    If proc match with parser, TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer is equal to 1:
        Let token be proc current_token with parser
        Set function_name to proc token_value with token
        proc advance with parser
    End If

    Note: Parse parameters (remaining arguments)
    Let parameters be proc create from List

    While proc match with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN from Lexer is equal to 0:
        Let arg be proc parse_argument with parser

        If arg is not equal to 0:
            proc append from List with parameters, arg
        Otherwise:
            proc advance with parser
        End If
    End While

    Note: Consume right parenthesis
    proc advance with parser

    Note: Parse body
    Let body be proc parse_block_until_keyword with parser

    Note: Expect endfunction
    Let token2 be proc current_token with parser
    Let type2 be proc token_type with token2

    If type2 is equal to TOKEN_ENDFUNCTION from Lexer:
        proc advance with parser
        If proc match with parser, TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN from Lexer is equal to 1:
            proc advance with parser
            While proc match with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN from Lexer is equal to 0:
                proc advance with parser
            End While
            proc advance with parser
        End If
    End If

    Return proc create_function with function_name, parameters, body
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses macro definitions, identical in shape to parse_function but
emitting a CMakeMacro and matching against `endmacro` instead of
`endfunction`.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes `macro`, expects `(`. Captures the macro name. Collects
parameter arguments until `)`. Parses body via
parse_block_until_keyword. Consumes `endmacro` and optional `()`.
Builds and returns a CMakeMacro.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_macro" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse macro definition: macro(name args...) ... endmacro()

    Note: Consume 'macro' keyword
    proc advance with parser

    Note: Expect left parenthesis
    If proc expect with parser, TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN from Lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Parse macro name (first argument)
    Let macro_name be 0
    If proc match with parser, TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer is equal to 1:
        Let token be proc current_token with parser
        Set macro_name to proc token_value with token
        proc advance with parser
    End If

    Note: Parse parameters (remaining arguments)
    Let parameters be proc create from List

    While proc match with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN from Lexer is equal to 0:
        Let arg be proc parse_argument with parser

        If arg is not equal to 0:
            proc append from List with parameters, arg
        Otherwise:
            proc advance with parser
        End If
    End While

    Note: Consume right parenthesis
    proc advance with parser

    Note: Parse body
    Let body be proc parse_block_until_keyword with parser

    Note: Expect endmacro
    Let token2 be proc current_token with parser
    Let type2 be proc token_type with token2

    If type2 is equal to TOKEN_ENDMACRO from Lexer:
        proc advance with parser
        If proc match with parser, TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN from Lexer is equal to 1:
            proc advance with parser
            While proc match with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN from Lexer is equal to 0:
                proc advance with parser
            End While
            proc advance with parser
        End If
    End If

    Return proc create_macro with macro_name, parameters, body
End Process

@Reasoning:
CMake conditions are syntactically just argument lists: `if(A AND B)`
is a head `if` with an argument list [A, AND, B]. This helper reuses
parse_argument for each item.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Expects `(`. Creates an empty List, loops while current token is not
`)`: parse_argument returns either an argument (appended) or 0 (in
which case the helper checks for EOF and bails, otherwise advances
past the offending token). Consumes the closing `)` and returns the
list.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_condition_list" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse condition as list of arguments (for if/while)

    Note: Expect left parenthesis
    If proc expect with parser, TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN from Lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create list for condition arguments
    Let condition be proc create from List

    Note: Parse arguments until right parenthesis
    While proc match with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN from Lexer is equal to 0:
        Let arg be proc parse_argument with parser

        If arg is not equal to 0:
            proc append from List with condition, arg
        Otherwise:
            Let token be proc current_token with parser
            Let type be proc token_type with token
            If type is equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
                Return 0
            End If
            proc advance with parser
        End If
    End While

    Note: Consume right parenthesis
    proc advance with parser

    Return condition
End Process

@Reasoning:
The body of every control-flow construct ends at a known terminating
keyword (endif/else/elseif/endforeach/endwhile/endfunction/endmacro).
This helper greedily parses statements until one of those is hit,
shared across parse_if / parse_foreach / parse_while / parse_function
/ parse_macro.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates a CMakeBlock. Loops while is_block_end_keyword returns 0:
checks for TOKEN_EOF (returns the partial block), calls
parse_statement; non-zero results are appended, 0 results trigger an
advance to skip the token. Does NOT consume the terminating keyword
— the calling parse_* helper does so based on which keyword it
expects.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_block_until_keyword" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse block of statements until control flow end keyword

    Let block be proc create_block

    If block is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Parse statements until we hit an end keyword
    While proc is_block_end_keyword with parser is equal to 0:
        Let token be proc current_token with parser
        Let type be proc token_type with token

        If type is equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
            Return block
        End If

        Let statement be proc parse_statement with parser

        If statement is not equal to 0:
            proc add_statement_to_block with block, statement
        Otherwise:
            proc advance with parser
        End If
    End While

    Return block
End Process

@Reasoning:
Tells parse_block_until_keyword when to stop. The set is the union
of every "end" keyword (endif, endforeach, endwhile, endfunction,
endmacro) plus the if-chain branch keywords (else, elseif) since
those also delimit a then-block.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads current_token's type via current_token + token_type. Returns
1 if the type matches any of TOKEN_ENDIF, TOKEN_ELSEIF, TOKEN_ELSE,
TOKEN_ENDFOREACH, TOKEN_ENDWHILE, TOKEN_ENDFUNCTION, TOKEN_ENDMACRO.
Returns 0 otherwise.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_block_end_keyword" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if current token is a block-ending keyword

    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    Let type be proc token_type with token

    If type is equal to TOKEN_ENDIF from Lexer:
        Return 1
    End If

    If type is equal to TOKEN_ELSEIF from Lexer:
        Return 1
    End If

    If type is equal to TOKEN_ELSE from Lexer:
        Return 1
    End If

    If type is equal to TOKEN_ENDFOREACH from Lexer:
        Return 1
    End If

    If type is equal to TOKEN_ENDWHILE from Lexer:
        Return 1
    End If

    If type is equal to TOKEN_ENDFUNCTION from Lexer:
        Return 1
    End If

    If type is equal to TOKEN_ENDMACRO from Lexer:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process
